(43, 12, 20, 44, 8, 27, 27, 'to worship', 'Worship by Diverse Peoples', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of worshippers from different nations coming to Jerusalem. The Greeks in John 12:20 and the Ethiopian eunuch in Acts 8:27 highlight the inclusivity of worship at the temple.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 20, 48, 2, 3, 3, 'Greeks among them', 'Connection of Greek Identity', 'This connection highlights the presence of Greeks in both passages. In John 12:20, Greeks come to worship, while Galatians 2:3 mentions Titus, a Greek, who was not compelled to follow Jewish customs.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 21, 40, 2, 2, 2, 'we would see Jesus', 'Desire to See Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize a desire to encounter Jesus. In John, individuals seek to see Jesus, while in Matthew, the Magi express a desire to find and worship the King of the Jews.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 21, 42, 19, 2, 4, 'we would see Jesus', 'Desire to See Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize a desire to see Jesus. In John, individuals approach Philip expressing their wish to see Him, while in Luke, Zaccheus actively seeks to see Jesus despite obstacles. This connection highlights the universal longing to encounter Jesus.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 21, 43, 6, 40, 40, 'we would see Jesus', 'Desire to See Jesus', 'This connection highlights the desire to see Jesus in both passages. In John 12:21, the request to see Jesus reflects the longing for understanding and belief, which is fulfilled in John 6:40, where seeing the Son leads to everlasting life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 21, 43, 14, 8, 9, 'we would see Jesus', 'Desire to See Jesus', 'This connection highlights Philip''s desire to see Jesus in both passages. In John 12:21, he is approached by those wanting to see Jesus, while in John 14:8-9, Philip directly asks Jesus to show them the Father, indicating a longing for divine revelation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 21, 40, 8, 9, 12, 'we would see Jesus', 'Faith and Inclusion in the Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of faith and the inclusion of outsiders in the kingdom of heaven. In John, the desire to see Jesus reflects a seeking faith, while in Matthew, the centurion''s faith leads to the promise of many from outside Israel being welcomed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 21, 45, 15, 8, 12, 'we would see Jesus', 'Gentiles Seeking Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Gentiles seeking Jesus, as seen in John 12:21 where they express a desire to see Him. Romans 15:8-12 further emphasizes the inclusion of Gentiles in God''s plan, celebrating their glorification of God for His mercy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 22, 41, 10, 13, 14, NULL, 'Children and Approach to Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of approaching Jesus, as seen in both passages. In John 12:22, individuals come to Jesus through Philip and Andrew, while in Mark 10:13-14, children are brought to Him for His blessing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 22, 42, 9, 49, 50, NULL, 'Unity in Following Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of inclusivity in following Jesus. Both passages emphasize the importance of recognizing those who act in Jesus'' name, regardless of their immediate association with the disciples.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 22, 43, 1, 40, 41, 'Andrew and Philip tell Jesus', 'Andrew''s Role in Both Passages', 'Both passages emphasize Andrew''s initiative in bringing others to Jesus. In John 1:40-41, Andrew finds Simon Peter and shares the news of the Messiah, while in John 12:22, Andrew, along with Philip, approaches Jesus, indicating his ongoing role in connecting people to Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 22, 43, 6, 8, 8, 'Andrew', 'Connection Through Andrew''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize Andrew''s involvement as a disciple. In John 12:22, Andrew is mentioned alongside Philip, while John 6:8 identifies him as Simon Peter''s brother, highlighting his significance among the disciples.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 22, 40, 10, 5, 5, 'Philip cometh and telleth Andrew', 'Disciples'' Role in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the active involvement of the disciples in bringing people to Jesus. In both passages, the disciples are depicted as intermediaries, either by communicating with Jesus or being sent forth to minister.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 23, 43, 13, 31, 32, 'the hour is come, that the Son of man should be glorified', 'Glorification of the Son of Man', 'This connection highlights the theme of glorification in both passages. In John 12:23, Jesus announces that ''the hour is come'' for his glorification, which is affirmed in John 13:31-32 as he states, ''Now is the Son of man glorified.''', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 23, 43, 17, 1, 5, 'the hour is come', 'Connection of Glorification Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of glorification, with Jesus stating that ''the hour is come'' for His glorification in both instances. This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' mission and the divine authority granted to Him.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 23, 23, 60, 9, 9, 'glorified', 'Connection of Glorification', 'This connection highlights the theme of glorification in both passages. In John 12:23, Jesus speaks of His glorification, while Isaiah 60:9 mentions glorification in relation to the Lord and Israel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 23, 41, 14, 41, 41, 'the hour is come', 'Connection of the Hour', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''the hour is come,'' indicating a pivotal moment in Jesus'' ministry. This connection highlights the transition from His glorification to His impending betrayal.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 23, 60, 2, 9, 10, NULL, 'Glorification and Identity in Christ', 'This connection highlights the transformation of believers as they are called into God''s light, paralleling Jesus'' glorification. Both passages emphasize a shift from a previous state to a new identity in relation to God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 23, 23, 49, 5, 6, 'the Son of man should be glorified', 'Glorification and Servanthood Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of glorification in both passages. In John 12:23, Jesus speaks of his glorification, while Isaiah 49:5-6 emphasizes the servant''s glory in the eyes of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 23, 40, 25, 31, 31, 'the Son of man should be glorified', 'Glory of the Son of Man', 'This connection highlights the theme of the glorification of the Son of Man in both passages. John 12:23 speaks of the hour of glorification, while Matthew 25:31 describes the Son of Man coming in his glory.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 24, 46, 15, 36, 38, 'Except a corn of wheat fall into the ground and die', 'Connection of Death and New Life', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of death for new life to emerge. John 12:24 speaks of a grain of wheat needing to die to produce fruit, while 1 Corinthians 15:36 highlights that what is sown must die to be quickened.', 'theme', 0.7899999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 24, 23, 53, 10, 12, 'if it die, it bringeth forth much fruit', 'Connection of Death and Fruitfulness', 'This connection highlights the theme of death leading to life and fruitfulness. In John 12:24, the death of the grain results in much fruit, paralleling Isaiah 53:10-12, where the suffering servant''s death leads to justification and the bearing of iniquities.', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 24, 58, 2, 9, 10, 'if it die, it bringeth forth much fruit', 'Connection of Death and Fruitfulness', 'This connection highlights the theme of death leading to life. In John 12:24, the death of the grain produces much fruit, while Hebrews 2:9-10 emphasizes Jesus tasting death to bring many to glory.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 24, 43, 12, 32, 33, 'if it die, it bringeth forth much fruit', 'Connection of Death and Fruitfulness', 'This connection highlights the theme of death leading to life. In John 12:24, the death of the grain results in much fruit, paralleling John 12:32-33, where Jesus'' being ''lifted up'' signifies his death that will draw all men to him.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 24, 19, 72, 16, 16, 'bringeth forth much fruit', 'Connection of Growth and Fruitfulness', 'This connection highlights the theme of growth through death and the resulting fruitfulness. Both passages emphasize the idea that from a small seed, much fruit can emerge, symbolizing abundance and flourishing.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 24, 66, 7, 9, 17, 'if it die, it bringeth forth much fruit', 'Connection of Life and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of transformation through death leading to new life. In John 12:24, the death of the grain results in much fruit, paralleling Revelation 7:14, where those who have washed their robes in the blood of the Lamb emerge from tribulation to eternal life.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 24, 19, 22, 22, 31, NULL, 'Connection of Seed and Fruit', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''seed'' leading to greater outcomes. In John 12:24, the seed must die to produce much fruit, while Psalms 22:30 speaks of a ''seed'' serving the Lord and declaring righteousness. This connection highlights the transformative power of sacrifice and growth.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 25, 40, 10, 39, 39, 'he that loveth his life shall lose it', 'Life and Loss Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the paradox of losing one''s life to gain eternal life. They highlight the idea that attachment to worldly life leads to loss, while sacrifice for a greater purpose leads to true fulfillment.', 'theme', 0.552, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 25, 42, 9, 23, 24, 'he that hateth his life in this world', 'Self-Denial and Eternal Life', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of losing one''s life to gain eternal life. They highlight the paradox of self-denial and the necessity of following Jesus for salvation.', 'theme', 0.503, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 25, 41, 8, 35, 35, 'he that loveth his life shall lose it', 'Life and Loss Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the paradox of losing one''s life to gain eternal life. They highlight the idea that valuing life in this world can lead to its loss, while sacrificing it for a greater purpose results in salvation.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
