VALUES
(43, 12, 25, 42, 17, 33, 33, 'he that loveth his life shall lose it', 'Life and Loss Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the paradox of losing one''s life to gain eternal life. They share similar phrasing about seeking to save or hate one''s life, highlighting a consistent theme of self-sacrifice for spiritual preservation.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 25, 40, 16, 25, 25, 'he that loveth his life shall lose it', 'Life and Loss Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the paradox of losing one''s life to gain eternal life. They highlight the idea that valuing earthly life can lead to spiritual loss, while sacrificing it for a higher purpose leads to true fulfillment.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 25, 44, 20, 24, 24, 'loveth his life shall lose it', 'Life and Ministry Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of not valuing one''s life in this world for the sake of a greater purpose. John 12:25 speaks of losing one''s life to gain eternal life, while Acts 20:24 reflects a similar sentiment of not counting life dear in the pursuit of ministry.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 25, 66, 12, 11, 11, 'loveth his life shall lose it', 'Connection of Life and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of valuing eternal life over earthly existence. John 12:25 speaks of hating one''s life to gain eternal life, while Revelation 12:11 highlights not loving one''s life even unto death.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 26, 51, 3, 24, 24, 'serve me', 'Service and Reward Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of serving Christ and the associated rewards. John 12:26 speaks of being honored by the Father for service, while Colossians 3:24 highlights receiving a reward from the Lord for serving Him.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 26, 9, 2, 30, 30, 'him will my Father honour', 'Connection of Honor and Service', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of honor linked to service and obedience. In John 12:26, serving Jesus leads to being honored by the Father, while 1 Samuel 2:30 states that those who honor God will be honored in return.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 26, 48, 1, 10, 10, NULL, 'Servanthood in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being a servant of Christ. John 12:26 highlights the honor given to those who serve Jesus, while Galatians 1:10 contrasts pleasing men with being a servant of Christ.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 26, 43, 10, 27, 27, 'let him follow me', 'Following the Shepherd', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of following Jesus. In John 12:26, serving Jesus involves following Him, while John 10:27 highlights that His sheep hear His voice and follow Him.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 26, 43, 17, 24, 24, 'where I am', 'Servanthood and Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being with Jesus. John 12:26 states that servants will be where He is, while John 17:24 expresses Jesus'' desire for His followers to be with Him. This connection highlights the importance of proximity to Christ for those who serve Him.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 26, 45, 1, 1, 1, 'serve me', 'Servanthood and Following Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of servanthood to Jesus. John 12:26 speaks of serving and following Christ, while Romans 1:1 identifies Paul as a servant of Jesus Christ, highlighting the call to serve in the gospel.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 26, 19, 91, 15, 15, NULL, 'Service and Divine Honor', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of service and the resulting honor from God. In John 12:26, serving Christ leads to being honored by the Father, while Psalms 91:15 promises deliverance and honor for those who call upon God.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 27, 43, 12, 23, 23, 'this hour', 'Connection of Jesus'' Hour', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of ''this hour'' in relation to Jesus'' mission. The first passage reveals Jesus'' troubled soul as he approaches this pivotal moment, while the second announces the arrival of that hour for his glorification.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 27, 58, 5, 7, 7, 'my soul troubled', 'Connection of Suffering and Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of deep emotional turmoil and the act of prayer in the face of impending death. John 12:27 speaks of a troubled soul, while Hebrews 5:7 describes prayers offered with strong crying and tears.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 27, 23, 38, 15, 15, 'What shall I say?', 'Connection of Troubled Souls', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of a troubled soul and the contemplation of what to say in times of distress. The phrase ''What shall I say?'' appears in both, linking their expressions of anguish and reflection.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 27, 40, 26, 42, 42, 'this hour', 'Connection of Jesus'' Troubled Soul', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' emotional turmoil as he faces his impending suffering. The phrase ''thy will be done'' in Matthew reflects his acceptance of the hour he refers to in John.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 27, 43, 13, 21, 21, 'my soul troubled', 'Connection of Troubled Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' troubled state. In John 12:27, he expresses his inner turmoil about his impending fate, while in John 13:21, he is again described as troubled in spirit due to betrayal.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 27, 19, 69, 1, 3, 'my soul troubled', 'Connection of Distress and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize a deep sense of trouble and a plea for salvation. John 12:27''s ''my soul troubled'' resonates with Psalms 69:1''s ''the waters are come in unto my soul,'' highlighting a shared theme of distress.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 27, 19, 88, 3, 3, 'my soul troubled', 'Connection of Troubled Souls', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of a troubled soul facing deep distress. John 12:27 reflects Jesus'' turmoil as he approaches his purpose, while Psalms 88:3 expresses a similar anguish of life nearing its end.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 28, 43, 13, 31, 32, 'glorified', 'Glorification of God and Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of glorification, with John 12:28 stating, ''I have both glorified it,'' and John 13:31 declaring, ''Now is the Son of man glorified.'' This connection highlights the continuity of God''s glory being revealed through Jesus.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 28, 40, 26, 42, 42, NULL, 'Divine Will and Glory', 'Both passages emphasize submission to God''s will. In John, the glorification of God''s name is central, while in Matthew, the plea for God''s will to be done reflects a similar theme of obedience.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 28, 66, 5, 9, 14, 'glorify thy name', 'Glorification of the Lamb', 'Both passages emphasize the glorification of God and the Lamb. John 12:28 speaks of God''s name being glorified, while Revelation 5:12 declares the Lamb''s worthiness to receive glory and honor.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 28, 43, 11, 40, 44, NULL, 'Glory of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of glorifying God. In John 12:28, Jesus calls for God''s name to be glorified, while in John 11:40, He indicates that belief will reveal the glory of God through the miracle of Lazarus''s resurrection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 28, 23, 49, 3, 7, 'glorified it, and will glorify it again', 'Glorification of God''s Servant', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of glorification associated with God''s servant. In John 12:28, the voice from heaven affirms the glorification of God''s name, while Isaiah 49:3 speaks of God''s servant, Israel, in whom He will be glorified.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 28, 40, 3, 17, 17, 'glorify thy name', 'Divine Affirmation of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the divine voice affirming Jesus'' identity and mission. Both passages feature a voice from heaven that emphasizes God''s approval and glory associated with Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 28, 50, 1, 6, 11, 'glorify thy name', 'Glorification of God', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of glorifying God. In John 12:28, the voice from heaven affirms God''s glory, while Philippians 1:11 speaks of being filled with the fruits of righteousness unto the glory and praise of God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 29, 18, 37, 2, 5, 'it thundered', 'Divine Voice and Thunder', 'Both passages emphasize the powerful voice of God, with John 12:29 mentioning the people''s perception of thunder and Job 37:2-5 describing God''s voice as thunderous and magnificent. This connection highlights the awe-inspiring nature of divine communication.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 29, 66, 6, 1, 1, 'it thundered', 'Thunder as Divine Communication', 'This connection highlights the motif of thunder as a form of divine communication. In both passages, the presence of thunder signifies a significant moment of revelation or response from God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 29, 66, 14, 2, 2, NULL, 'Voice and Thunder Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the powerful nature of divine communication, with John noting the voice perceived as thunder and Revelation describing a voice as ''the voice of great thunder.'' This connection highlights the awe-inspiring presence of God''s voice.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 29, 2, 19, 16, 16, 'it thundered', 'Divine Communication Through Thunder', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine communication through thunder. In both passages, the presence of thunder signifies a powerful encounter with God, eliciting fear and awe among the people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 29, 2, 20, 18, 18, 'thundered', 'Connection of Divine Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the phenomenon of thunder as a means of divine communication. In John 12:29, the crowd interprets the voice as thunder, while in Exodus 20:18, the people witness thunderings associated with God''s presence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
