(43, 12, 29, 18, 40, 9, 9, 'thundered', 'Divine Voice and Thunder', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s powerful voice, as both passages reference thunder. In John, the crowd interprets a divine communication as thunder, while Job directly questions if anyone can thunder like God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 29, 26, 10, 5, 5, NULL, 'Divine Voice and Sound', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine communication through sound. Both passages emphasize the powerful auditory experiences associated with God''s voice, whether it is perceived as thunder or the sound of wings.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 30, 43, 11, 42, 42, 'for your sakes', 'Divine Communication for Belief', 'Both passages emphasize that Jesus'' words and actions are intended for the benefit of the people present, highlighting the purpose of divine communication to foster belief. In each instance, Jesus acknowledges that his statements are made for the sake of those who hear them.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 30, 43, 11, 15, 15, 'for your sakes', 'Connection of Purpose for Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the purpose of Jesus'' actions for the sake of others'' belief. In John 12:30, Jesus indicates that the voice was for the benefit of the listeners, while in John 11:15, He expresses gladness for their sake to foster belief.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 30, 43, 5, 34, 34, 'for your sakes', 'Testimony and Salvation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of testimony and its purpose. In both passages, Jesus emphasizes that the voice or testimony serves a greater purpose for the listeners'' salvation.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 30, 47, 8, 9, 9, 'for your sakes', 'Connection of Sacrifice for Others', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' actions being for the benefit of others. Both passages emphasize that Jesus'' experiences, whether the voice from heaven or his poverty, were for the sake of humanity.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 31, 47, 4, 4, 4, 'prince of this world', 'Judgment and the God of This World', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and the influence of the ''prince of this world'' and ''god of this world'' in blinding unbelievers. Both passages emphasize the spiritual conflict and the consequences of this influence on faith.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 31, 62, 3, 8, 8, 'prince of this world be cast out', 'Judgment and Destruction of Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and the defeat of evil. John 12:31 speaks of the prince of this world being cast out, while 1 John 3:8 emphasizes the purpose of the Son of God to destroy the works of the devil.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 31, 62, 5, 19, 19, 'prince of this world', 'Judgment and Wickedness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and the state of the world. Both passages emphasize the negative condition of the world, with John 12:31 referencing the judgment and casting out of the prince of this world, while 1 John 5:19 states that the whole world lies in wickedness.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 31, 43, 14, 30, 30, 'prince of this world', 'Connection of the Prince of the World', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the ''prince of this world.'' In John 12:31, the prince is cast out, while in John 14:30, he approaches but finds nothing in Jesus. This highlights the conflict between Jesus and the prince.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 31, 49, 6, 12, 12, 'prince of this world', 'Spiritual Warfare and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the conflict against spiritual forces. John 12:31 speaks of the prince of this world being cast out, while Ephesians 6:12 identifies rulers of darkness as adversaries in this spiritual struggle.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 31, 51, 2, 15, 15, 'prince of this world', 'Judgment and Triumph Over Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against evil forces. Both passages emphasize the defeat of the ''prince of this world'' and the triumph over ''principalities and powers.''', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 31, 58, 2, 14, 14, 'prince of this world be cast out', 'Judgment and Power of Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and the defeat of evil. John 12:31 speaks of the prince of this world being cast out, while Hebrews 2:14 mentions destroying him that had the power of death, the devil.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 32, 43, 3, 14, 14, 'if I be lifted up from the earth', 'Connection of Lifted Up', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''lifted up.'' The lifting of the serpent in the wilderness serves as a typological foreshadowing of Jesus being lifted up, which will draw all men to Him.', 'typology', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 32, 43, 8, 28, 28, 'lifted up', 'Connection of Being Lifted Up', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''lifted up.'' In John 12:32, Jesus states that he will draw all men when he is lifted up, while in John 8:28, he indicates that knowing him comes after he is lifted up. This connection highlights the significance of his crucifixion and revelation.', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 32, 60, 2, 24, 24, 'lifted up from the earth', 'Connection of Suffering and Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' sacrificial act. Both passages emphasize the drawing of people to Him through His suffering and the healing that results from it.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 32, 54, 2, 6, 6, 'draw all men unto me', 'Connection of Universal Redemption', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus drawing all people to himself through his sacrificial act. Both passages emphasize the concept of a ransom for all, indicating a universal scope of salvation.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 32, 62, 2, 2, 2, 'all men unto me', 'Universal Scope of Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of drawing all people to Christ through His sacrifice. Both passages emphasize the inclusivity of His atonement, as ''all men'' and ''the whole world'' suggest a universal reach.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 32, 48, 3, 13, 13, 'if I be lifted up from the earth', 'Connection of Redemption and Lifting Up', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s sacrificial act. Both passages emphasize the significance of being ''lifted up'' and the curse associated with hanging on a tree, linking Christ''s crucifixion to the redemption of humanity.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 32, 58, 2, 9, 9, 'draw all men unto me', 'Connection of Universal Drawing', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of Jesus'' role in drawing all men to himself through his suffering and death. John 12:32 highlights the act of being ''lifted up'' to draw people, while Hebrews 2:9 speaks of Jesus tasting death for ''every man,'' indicating a universal reach.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 33, 43, 18, 32, 32, 'what death he should die', 'Connection of Jesus'' Death Prediction', 'Both passages emphasize what death he should die, linking Jesus'' prediction to its fulfillment. This connection highlights the continuity of Jesus'' foretelling and the events that transpired.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 33, 43, 21, 19, 19, 'what death he should die', 'Connection of Death and Glory', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of death in relation to glorifying God. In John 12:33, the focus is on the type of death Jesus would face, while John 21:19 highlights how this death would ultimately glorify God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 34, 26, 37, 24, 25, 'Christ abideth for ever', 'Eternal Kingship Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of eternal leadership. Both passages reference a figure who will reign forever, with John mentioning the ''Christ abideth for ever'' and Ezekiel stating ''my servant David shall be their prince for ever.''', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 34, 23, 9, 7, 7, 'Christ abideth for ever', 'Eternal Kingship and Christ''s Role', 'This connection highlights the theme of eternal reign. Both passages emphasize the idea of a lasting kingdom, with John referencing the eternal nature of Christ and Isaiah proclaiming the everlasting government of David''s throne.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 34, 27, 7, 14, 14, 'Christ abideth for ever', 'Eternal Kingdom Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of everlasting dominion. Both passages emphasize the eternal nature of the kingdom associated with the Son of Man.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 34, 19, 110, 4, 4, 'Christ abideth for ever', 'Eternal Priesthood Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of eternal roles, as both passages reference the concept of enduring positions: Christ abides forever and is linked to the priesthood after Melchizedek. The mention of ''for ever'' in both verses emphasizes the permanence of these roles.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 34, 27, 2, 44, 44, 'abideth for ever', 'Eternal Kingdom Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of eternal existence. Both passages emphasize the idea of something that abides or stands forever, linking the concept of Christ''s eternal nature with God''s everlasting kingdom.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 34, 10, 7, 13, 13, 'Christ abideth for ever', 'Eternal Kingship Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of an everlasting kingdom. John 12:34 questions the identity of the ''Son of man,'' while 2 Samuel 7:13 speaks of establishing a throne forever, linking the idea of eternal reign.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 34, 43, 3, 14, 16, 'The Son of man must be lifted up', 'Connection of the Son of Man', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of the Son of Man being lifted up. The SOURCE verse questions the identity of the Son of Man, while the TARGET passage clarifies this by linking it to Moses'' serpent, indicating a pivotal moment for salvation.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 35, 43, 12, 46, 46, 'light with you', 'Light and Darkness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light as essential for guidance and belief. The first passage warns about walking in darkness, while the second affirms that Jesus is the light that prevents one from abiding in darkness.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
