(43, 12, 35, 43, 16, 16, 16, 'a little while', 'Light and Seeing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of visibility and presence. In both passages, the phrase ''a little while'' emphasizes a temporary state, linking the idea of walking in light with the notion of seeing Jesus before his departure.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 35, 49, 5, 8, 8, 'walk while ye have the light', 'Walking in Light', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of walking in light rather than darkness. John 12:35 warns about the danger of darkness, while Ephesians 5:8 encourages believers to walk as children of light.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 35, 62, 1, 6, 7, 'walk while ye have the light', 'Walking in the Light', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of walking in the light to avoid darkness. John 12:35 warns about the consequences of walking in darkness, while 1 John 1:6-7 highlights the necessity of walking in the light for true fellowship.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 35, 24, 13, 16, 17, 'light with you', 'Light and Darkness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between light and darkness, warning against the consequences of ignoring the light. John 12:35 speaks of walking in the light while it is present, while Jeremiah 13:16 warns of stumbling in darkness if one does not heed God''s call.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 35, 23, 2, 5, 5, 'walk while ye have the light', 'Walking in the Light', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of walking in the light. John 12:35 warns against darkness, while Isaiah 2:5 invites to walk in the light of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 35, 52, 5, 5, 8, 'light with you', 'Light and Darkness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between light and darkness, urging believers to walk in the light and remain vigilant. The call to be sober and watchful in 1 Thessalonians parallels Jesus'' warning about walking in the light while it is present.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 36, 49, 5, 8, 8, 'children of light', 'Children of Light Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''children of light.'' John 12:36 encourages belief in the light, while Ephesians 5:8 states believers are now light in the Lord, urging them to walk as such.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 36, 43, 8, 59, 59, 'did hide himself from them', 'Connection of Jesus Hiding', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus hiding himself from others. In John 12:36, he hides after speaking about light, while in John 8:59, he hides from those who seek to harm him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 36, 52, 5, 5, 5, 'children of light', 'Children of Light Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''children of light.'' This connection highlights the call to live in accordance with light and truth, contrasting with darkness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 36, 42, 16, 8, 8, 'children of light', 'Children of Light Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''children of light.'' John 12:36 encourages belief in the light, while Luke 16:8 contrasts the wisdom of the children of this world with the children of light, highlighting a thematic connection regarding spiritual awareness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 36, 43, 1, 7, 7, 'believe in the light', 'Connection of Light and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of believing in the light. John 12:36 encourages belief in the light to become children of light, while John 1:7 highlights the purpose of bearing witness to the light for belief.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 36, 44, 13, 47, 48, 'believe in the light', 'Light and Salvation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of light as a symbol of salvation. In John, Jesus encourages belief in the light, while in Acts, the light is presented as a means of salvation for the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 36, 23, 60, 1, 1, 'believe in the light', 'Connection of Light and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of light as a divine presence. John speaks of believing in the light to become children of light, while Isaiah calls for arising and shining because the light has come.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 37, 42, 16, 31, 31, 'believed not on him', 'Unbelief Despite Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief despite clear evidence. Both passages emphasize that even extraordinary signs, like miracles or resurrection, do not guarantee faith.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 37, 43, 1, 11, 11, 'believed not on him', 'Rejection of Jesus by His Own', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of belief in Jesus despite His miracles. They highlight the theme of rejection by those who should have accepted Him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 37, 43, 15, 24, 24, 'done so many miracles before them', 'Miracles and Unbelief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of disbelief despite witnessing miraculous works. John 12:37 notes the lack of belief despite miracles, while John 15:24 highlights the consequences of seeing these works and still rejecting Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 37, 40, 11, 20, 20, NULL, 'Miracles and Unbelief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the failure to believe despite witnessing mighty works. John highlights the lack of belief in miracles, while Matthew addresses the cities that did not repent after experiencing those works.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 37, 43, 11, 42, 42, 'believed not on him', 'Belief and Miracles Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in relation to miracles. In both passages, the emphasis is on the necessity of belief, as seen in the miracles performed and the call for faith in Jesus'' divine mission.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 38, 23, 53, 1, 1, 'Who hath believed our report?', 'Connection of Prophetic Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the direct quotation of Isaiah 53:1 in John 12:38, emphasizing the theme of belief in the report of the Lord. Both passages ask the same rhetorical questions, linking the prophetic message to its fulfillment in the New Testament.', 'quotation', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 38, 45, 10, 16, 16, 'Lord, who hath believed our report?', 'Connection of Isaiah''s Prophecy', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase, ''Lord, who hath believed our report?'' highlighting a shared theme of disbelief in the message of God. This connection illustrates the continuity of Isaiah''s prophetic words in the context of the New Testament.', 'quotation', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 38, 46, 1, 24, 24, 'who hath believed our report?', 'Power and Belief in Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in God''s revelation. Both passages emphasize the response to God''s power, with John referencing belief in the report and Corinthians affirming Christ as the power of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 38, 47, 4, 3, 6, 'who hath believed our report?', 'Connection of Belief and Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of belief and the revelation of God''s light. John 12:38 questions who has believed the report, while 2 Corinthians 4:3-6 discusses how the minds of unbelievers are blinded, preventing them from seeing the light of the gospel.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 38, 40, 16, 17, 17, 'arm of the Lord', 'Revelation of the Father', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine revelation. In both passages, the concept of revelation is emphasized, with John referencing the ''arm of the Lord'' and Matthew noting that the Father reveals truth to Peter.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 38, 44, 8, 28, 30, 'Esaias the prophet', 'Connection of Prophetic Fulfillment', 'Both passages emphasize the prophet Esaias, highlighting the theme of belief in the report of the Lord. The mention of Esaias in both contexts connects the fulfillment of prophecy with the act of understanding scripture.', 'prophecy', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 38, 44, 13, 27, 29, 'that the saying of Esaias the prophet might be fulfilled', 'Fulfillment of Prophecy', 'Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of prophetic words regarding Jesus. John 12:38 references Isaiah''s prophecy about belief and revelation, while Acts 13:27-29 discusses how the rulers of Jerusalem fulfilled the prophets by condemning Jesus.', 'prophecy', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 39, 23, 6, 9, 10, 'could not believe', 'Connection of Unbelief and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of unbelief in both passages. John 12:39 refers to Isaiah''s prophecy about the people''s inability to believe, which is elaborated in Isaiah 6:9-10, where the people''s hearts are made unresponsive to understanding.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 39, 43, 5, 44, 44, 'could not believe', 'Belief and Honor Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the difficulty of belief. In John 12:39, the inability to believe is linked to external influences, while John 5:44 highlights the issue of seeking honor from others instead of God, suggesting that misplaced priorities hinder faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 39, 43, 10, 38, 38, 'could not believe', 'Connection of Belief and Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in relation to the works of Jesus. In both passages, the inability to believe is contrasted with the call to recognize the divine presence through actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 39, 61, 2, 14, 14, 'could not believe', 'Connection of Unbelief and Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the inability to believe and the nature of sin. John 12:39 highlights a spiritual blindness that prevents belief, while 2 Peter 2:14 describes individuals who are entrenched in sin and deception, suggesting a parallel in the consequences of unbelief.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 39, 23, 44, 18, 20, 'could not believe', 'Spiritual Blindness and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual blindness and lack of understanding present in both passages. John 12:39 indicates that belief is hindered, paralleling Isaiah 44:18-20, which describes how God has shut their eyes and hearts to understanding.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
